### Notes

  * Problem analysis
The problems consists in arranging the n chairs in a hall. Each parliamentarian should sit next to a chair of the same party. For the simplicity, we are talking about Democratic and Republican parties here. They are evenly distributed in the assembly hall. For each chair there are four neighbours. But we are trying to find only one solution.
  * Algorithm
The algorithm starts by dividing each chair to four parts. The first part that is the left side of this chair is the left side of all chairs that are in front of it. The second part is the right side of this chair. Similarly we can divide each side of chairs to two parts: the left side and the right side.
Now we move to the second part of the hall: rows. Each parliamentarian should be placed such that its left neighbour is the left neighbour of the chair which he or she is sitting now and right neighbour is the right neighbour of this chair. The first part is the upper row and the second part is the lower row.
Finally we come to the last parts of the problem: seats. We try to give a right seat to each parliamentarian. If the two parliamentarians are of different partities, they can sit next to each other.
  * Complexity
The time complexity of this problem is O(b) because we are only going over rows. The space complexity is O(n) because we only keep two variables per row in the hall.
  * Code
We define an array to indicate what chairs are given seats in the hall. The element in this array is either 0 or 1. 0 stands for empty seat and 1 stands for filled seat.
  * Code
The function `check` checks if there are pairs of parliamentarians that are in a row and have different party. The return value is the existence of such pairs of parliamentarians.
  * Code
The `main` function reads input and tries all possible ways for seats.
