# Problem 5
### Problem description:
Little Tim has k colored tiles, one tile is colored blue. Tim needs to divide these tiles into n pairs of equal size. Each pair consists of two identical colors (either blue or some other color). However, a pair must contain blue on the left and a color on the right side. Otherwise, the pair is broken and Tim loses. Help Tim.

### Input specification:
The first line contains integer k (1 ≤ k ≤ 105), the number of colored tiles. In the second line, the number n (1 ≤ n ≤ k) is given.

### Output specification:
If Tim can split k tiles into n pairs, print two lines. The first line must contain integer n, which represents the number of pairs. The second line must contain n positive integers (the size of a pair), separated by spaces. In case of a lack of pairs, print a single integer -1.

### Sample Input:
100 4

### Sample Output:
4
10 10

### Explanation:

#### Explanation:
There are at least 3 pairs of equal sizes: (10, 10), (50, 50), (25, 25), and (50, 25), which can be split into 4 pairs of size 10 and 10. Therefore, we print 4 (the number of pairs) and two lines with 10 and 10, which gives the size of each pair. Note, that the sizes are not necessary sorted.
#### Solution:
```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int k,n;
    cin>>k>>n;
    int s=(k/2)+1;
    if(k%2==1){
        if(s==n){
            cout<<n<<" "<<s<<endl;
        }
        else if(s>n){
            cout<<"-1"<<endl;
        }
        else{
            s=n;
            int t=(k-s)/(n-1);
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                cout<<t<<" "<<s<<endl;
            }
        }
    }
    else{
        if(s>n){
            cout<<"-1"<<endl;
        }
        else{
            s=n;
            int t=(k-2*s)/(n-1);
            cout<<n<<endl;
            for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
                cout<<t+1<<" "<<s<<endl;
            }
        }
    }
}
