### Analysis:
Polycarpus wants to pour the same amount of cola to everybody. If all the mugs were empty, he needs to pour the volume of the cola in the bottle into all of them. If some of the mugs were not empty yet, he needs to pour the difference between the amount of cola in a mug and the amount of cola in the bottle into that mug and then pour the volume of cola in the bottle into the remaining mugs. If any of the mugs are not empty, Polycarpus wants the total volume of cola in all the mugs to be the same. Because we need to use a single bottle, and Polycarpus wants the bottle to be empty after pouring, he needs to pour the same amount of cola into each mug. Thus, for all of the mugs to be filled, we need to divide the amount of cola in the bottle into the number of mugs. If the amount of cola in the bottle is not a multiple of the number of mugs, we can't pour the same amount of cola to each mug, so we can't fulfill the conditions to make each mug full of cola.

Thus, I wrote a program to solve the problem. First, Polycarpus determines how much he needs to pour into each mug. If the total volume of the drink in all the mugs is less than the volume of the bottle left, he fills the mugs in descending order, the first mug with the most left, the second one with the second most left, and so on. If the total volume of the drink in all the mugs is greater than the volume of the bottle left, he pours the bottle into the mugs in descending order, until the volume of the drink in each mug is the same. I used an average to determine how much he needs to pour into each mug to ensure that the condition was satisfied, because I don't know what the distribution of the drink in the mugs is, and thus I can't determine the volume of the drink he needs to pour into each mug.

