7. Analysis: Here we have to calculate the maximum number of pieces that Polycarpus can split the ribbon into by using only the lengths a, b, and c that have been given.  The first thing that we do is to initialize all of our variables. The first variable is the length of the ribbon and it is initialized with the variable n. The second three variables are the acceptable lengths of the ribbon pieces after the cutting. 
We start a nested loop of three loops that have a for loop in each of them that has an index value that goes from 0 to n. The outer for loop variable i has an index value that goes from 0 to n and each iteration of the outer for loop is a different length that the piece can have. The inner for loop variables j and k have an index value that goes from 0 to n. The inner loop variables j and k are each for a different length that the piece can have. Since we want to split the ribbon into the a, b, and c lengths of pieces we need a separate loop for each of these lengths. The inner for loop for each length has an index value that goes from 0 to n and each iteration of the inner for loop is a different possible length for the piece. 
For each possible length we check if that length is acceptable and if both the length and the length of the second piece that we can get by joining the two pieces together is acceptable. If they are acceptable we add one to the number of pieces we can get from the ribbon and break out of the inner for loop and go on to the next outer for loop iteration. If we finish the outer for loop then we break out of the middle for loop and go on to the next outer for loop iteration and so on.
The code will only exit the loops when we find a way to split the ribbon into the a, b, and c lengths of pieces.

