### Explanation
Here is a brief explanation for the code.
- The first few lines are the input and output parts.
- The next line includes a struct named Pos which includes two integer variables x and y. This struct is used for the position of a square on the board.
- The vector d has the same size as the chessboard. It is used to track the minimum number of rows/columns needed to be painted for each square of the board.
- The loop starts by inputting the rows of the board.
- For each row, a loop checks whether each square on the row has been painted or not.
- If the square is not painted, the position of the square is entered into the vector b.
- The value of m (the number of painted squares) is increased by 1.
- The line d[0] is initialized to be 0.
- The for loop starts by setting a minimum number, min, to the current value of the value in d at the position of the first element of b.
- The position of the minimum, pos, is initialized to the position of the element with the smallest value.
- The for loop loops through each of the elements of d. If d[j] is not equal to INT_MAX and it has a lower value than min, then pos=j, and min=d[j].
- If min is equal to INT_MAX, then the board cannot be painted.
- If the position of the square is in the board, d[pos] is initialized to the value of d[pos]+1.
- c[pos][k] (for k=0 to n-1) is initialized to 'B'.
- For every pair in b, if the row and column of the pair are within the size of the chessboard, then d[pos] is initialized to the value of d[pos]+1.
- If d[pos] is equal to the length of the board, then the number of rows/columns painted is increased by 1.
- The loop stops when every square of the board is painted.
- The variable res, which stores the number of rows and columns painted, is initialized to the size of the board, INT_MAX.
- For every square of the board, the for loop starts by setting tmp to 0.
- For every square of the board, if c[i][j] is equal to 'B', then tmp is increased by 1.
- If tmp is equal to the size of the board, then res is assigned to the minimum value of res and tmp.
- The for loop stops when every square has been counted.
- The result is output.

### Time and Space Complexity Analysis
Time complexity: O(n). For each line, we initialize the row. The for loop loops through n elements in total. The minimum number of rows/columns painted is obtained in the outer loop, and for every square, the number of rows/columns painted is obtained in O(n). Therefore, the time complexity is O(n).

Space complexity: O(n). The space complexity is calculated based on the struct Pos, vector b, and vector d. For every square of the board, a new entry is made in vector b. For every square of the board, a new entry is made in vector d. For every entry of vector d, a new value is assigned. For every square of the board, vector c needs to have a new entry, which requires O(n). Therefore, the space complexity is O(n).

