### 1. The description
It’s about Petya, a student, who has noticed that he frequently types wrong words on the screen. For instance, it’s possible to write “abdrakadabra” instead of “abrakadabra” with one extra letter “d”. If the same problem is with a printed word, then the word becomes not only incorrect, but even unrecognizable, for instance “aa” instead of “a”. And how does Petya deal with that issue? The problem is obvious: the spell-checker underlines every wrong word, but it’s Petya’s responsibility to fix the problem, either he spends time for that or asks someone else to do so. However, it’s not only frustrating, but also time-consuming. Petya decides to take it upon himself and in front of everybody, not to fix his mistakes later, but to fix them right away. The idea is not to find the way of fixing mistakes, but to make it as easy as possible. The first step is to understand what happens when a word from the printed version is wrong. For instance, if Petya sees “abdrakadabra”, the same word is written on the paper, but only the first two letters are different (there is “d” instead of “r”). Hence, the same word “abrakadabra” from the paper can be made with the first word “abdrakadabra”. Hence, the function should remove an extra symbol from “abdrakadabra” and receive the correct word “abrakadabra”. The goal is to find out which symbol should be removed and make the same word “abrakadabra”.
### 2. The program
Here is the code. As you can see, I use only two variables:
* i - is the number of the first element of the difference array.
* counter - is the number of extra symbols to be removed from the first word.
I use the difference array to find the difference in the two words. The function will find out which symbol must be removed and return the number of extra symbols. Then this value is used to remove symbols from the first string.
```
#include<bits/stdc++.h>

using namespace std;

// Finds extra symbols to delete.
// Returns the number of such symbols.
int delete_extra_symbol(char str1[], char str2[]) {
    int diff_arr[100]; // Array of differences
    int i = 0; // Index of first symbol of difference in a difference array
    int diff_len = 0; // Length of a difference array
    int counter = 0; // Number of extra symbols to be removed

    for (int j = 0; j < strlen(str1); j++) {
        if (str1[j]!= str2[j]) {
            diff_arr[diff_len] = j + 1;
            i = i + 1;
            diff_len++;
        }
    }

    if (diff_len == 1) {
        return 0;
    } else {
        counter = abs(diff_arr[i] - diff_arr[i + 1]);
        return counter;
    }
}

// Removes extra symbols from the first string.
// Parameters:
// First - the first word.
// Second - the second word.
// Num - the number of extra symbols to be removed.
// Result - the string with corrected length.
void delete_num_symbols(char* first, char* second, int num) {
    int counter = 0;
    for (int j = 0; j < strlen(second); j++) {
        if (counter < num) {
            first[j] = second[j];
            counter++;
        } else {
            break;
        }
    }
    first[j] = '\0'; // Null symbol indicates the end of a string
}

int main() {
    int test_cases = 1;
    char str1[101];
    char str2[101];

    // Read input
    scanf("%d", &test_cases);
    for (int i = 0; i < test_cases; i++) {
        // Read first word
        scanf("%s", str1);
        // Read second word
        scanf("%s", str2);

        // Find extra symbols to remove
        int num = delete_extra_symbol(str1, str2);

        // Remove extra symbols from the first word
        delete_num_symbols(str1, str2, num);

        // Print result
        printf("%s\n", str1);

        // Move to the next pair of words
        printf("\n");
    }
    return 0;
}
