**Note**. The solution presented here is not optimized. It is the solution that I understood and I wrote down. I tried to write the code in a standard way, that is it is possible to read and understand.

**Input**
The input of the program is a set of edges. Each edge represents a railway between two towns, i.e. two nodes in the graph. The first token in each line defines the source and the second token defines the destination. All the edges are given in the input.

**Output**
The output of the program is a number that represents the minimum time that the later vehicle takes to reach the town n, except if the solution does not exist, the output of the program is the word -1. 

**Solution**
The solution presented here is the one that I found. This problem was one of the most hard problems that I solved. The solution that I found is very similar to the solution that I used in the HRP. Here I present the solution that I used in the HRP and this is the one that I am going to describe. First of all I will describe my first solution. The first one is not the best solution. It is the one that I use in the HRP. 

**Solution Description**

The first solution that I am going to describe is the one that I use in the HRP. The solution is based on DFS and the use of a bit array. This solution has a time complexity of O(n^2). This is because it is necessary to explore the graph with a depth of n. I describe the solution with details and I describe step by step the execution of the algorithm. 


The algorithm uses a bit array in order to check if a edge is in the current tree or not. This bit array is used to check if a edge was traversed before. It is initialized in a null state at the beginning. At each iteration of the algorithm, we traverse all the vertices in the current tree, in order to compute the successor set of every vertex.

**Execution of the algorithm**

First, we initialize the set of visited vertices with empty. After that, we initialize an auxiliary set of vertex with all the vertices in the graph.

We initialize the bit array as null. At the beginning of each step of the DFS, we traverse all the vertices in the current tree and we mark each vertex as visited in the bit array. Each vertex that is traversed is inserted in the set of visited vertices.

We begin the algorithm by visiting the source vertex. 

The algorithm terminates when we have visited all the vertices in the graph. 


