**Second Solution**

The second solution that I am going to present is the second solution that I found. This solution is based on DP and this solution has a time complexity of O(n^3). This is because each node is visited three times, and we visit all the nodes. 

**Solution Description**

The solution that I am going to present is based on the concept of reachability and unreachability of a vertex with respect to a set of vertices. Each vertex is reachable of unreachable regarding a set of vertices if there exists a path in the graph with respect to this set of vertices. If we know whether the reachability of a vertex and all its successors, we can determine the reachability of all vertices in the graph.

**Execution of the algorithm**

First, we initialize the graph with the help of a bit array that records if a vertex is in the graph. 

We initialize the vector as empty. 

After that, we initialize an auxiliary vector of vertices with all the vertices of the graph. 

We initialize the bit array as null.

We begin the algorithm by visiting the source vertex. 

After that, we visit all the vertices in the current tree with the help of the DFS algorithm. At each iteration, we mark each vertex as visited in the bit array. 

We mark each vertex as reachable or unreachable according to the state of the DP vector at the parent of the current vertex. 

We continue the DFS algorithm until we visit all the vertices of the graph.

