### Response explanation:

If k=0, there is only one way to divide the class and each student works independently. Hence the answer is 1.
In each step, the current student i selects another student and form a group, and the maximum time it takes i and j to work together is the maximum of their own time. The minimum of all the maximum time takes among all the groups is the maximum time takes among all the students, hence the first round of the divide-and-conquer algorithm. In the second round, we repeat the same process until the minimum of the maximum times is 0.  The key idea of this approach is to compare each student with their previous group of size m - 1. In the third round, we find the new maximum time takes among all the groups. This process continues until all the students work alone. Note that at each round, there must be a student working alone because the sum of each group is greater than the maximum time. Hence if there is no student working alone, the last student should be included in some other group before. 

Time Complexity: O(n * n)

Space complexity: O(n)

